{{Infobox geographical indication | name = Double church | color = | logo = | image = <!--Write image name without File: or Image:--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | alternative names = | description = Double naves standing side by side and separated by a common wall | type = Church design | area = Byzantine | country = <!-- Country --> | registered = <!-- Registration year --> | material = | official website = <!-- {{URL|wwww.example.org}} --> }}
{{distinguish|Simultaneum|Double chapel}} A '''Double church''',<ref name="Encyclopaedia"/> or '''twin church''',<ref name="Mihaljević"/> is a church design found in [[Byzantine architecture]]. The double church design of the [[Üçayak Byzantine Church]] features double [[nave]]s standing side by side and separated by a common wall. The twin church design at Üçayak has two [[nave]]s each with a separate semi-circular [[apse]]. Each apse includes a rectangular bay in front of it.<ref name="Encyclopaedia">{{cite web | last=Toivanen |first=Hanna-Riitta |title=Byzantine Church at Üçayak (Kirşehir, Cappadocia)|url=http://asiaminor.ehw.gr/forms/filePage.aspx?lemmaId=3931|publisher=Encyclopaedia of the Hellenic World, Asia Minor|date=2001|quote=Close to the ruined church there was a spring of water, but no material remains have been found, which means, that this church was built originally in a completely isolated and remote place.}}</ref><ref name="Mihaljević">{{cite journal |last1=Mihaljević |first1=Marina |title=Üçayak: a forgotten Byzantine church|journal=[[Byzantinische Zeitschrift]]|date=2014|volume=2|issue=107|pages=725–754, pl. I-V |url=https://www.academia.edu/10536446/_%C3%9C%C3%A7ayak_a_forgotten_Byzantine_church_Byzantinische_Zeitschrift_107.2_2014_735-754_pl._I-V|quote=Regarding the possible function of the twin-church of Üçayak, this article argues for the burial and commemorative functions, which often motivated the double arrangement in Cappadocian rock-cut churches. ... The edifice is, namely, arranged as a twin church, which makes it relatively uncommon within the context of Byzantine architecture (fig. 1).}}</ref>
