{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} [[File:Public Seal of Niue.svg|thumb|250px|The Seal of Niue]] The '''Seal of Niue''', or the '''Public Seal of Niue''', is the [[official seal]] of [[Niue]]. It was created in 1974 when Niue gained independence and joined into [[Associated state|free association]] with [[New Zealand]].
==History== Before 1974 Niue used the [[Coat of Arms of New Zealand]]. The [[Niue Constitution Act]], passed in 1974, provided for a unique seal to be created for Niue. The Seal was to be held by the [[List of Speakers of the Niue Assembly|Speaker of the Niue Assembly]], and was to be used to authenticate public documents or to affirm creation of new laws by the Cabinet of Niue. The Speaker is also responsible for ensuring that the Seal is not misused.<ref>{{cite paper |url=http://www.victoria.ac.nz/law/nzacl/PDFS/Vol_17_2011/Quentin-Baxter.pdf |title=The role of the Speaker in the Constitution of Niue |work=NZACL Yearbook |publisher=[[University of Wellington]] |page=22 |accessdate=16 July 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726111234/http://www.victoria.ac.nz/law/nzacl/PDFS/Vol_17_2011/Quentin-Baxter.pdf |archivedate=26 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> All judicial notices in Niue are affixed with the Seal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1974/0042/latest/DLM413412.html |title=Niue Constitution Act 1974 No 42 (as at 01 April 1988), Public Act The Seal of Niue – New Zealand Legislation |publisher=Legislation.govt.nz |date=1 April 1988 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> In 1977, after a request from the Niue Assembly, the [[Parliament of New Zealand]] passed the Seal of New Zealand Act with an amendment relating to Niue to bring the design of the Public Seal of Niue into line with the other nations in the [[Realm of New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz/gpacts/public/text/1977/se/001se7.html |title=Application of Act to Cook Island, Niue, and Tokelau |publisher=Legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz |date=28 February 1977 |accessdate=16 July 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726141111/http://legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz/gpacts/public/text/1977/se/001se7.html |archivedate=26 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Before 2007 the Seal of Niue was used in [[Tokelau]] to confirm the passage of legislation. In 2007 the Tokelau Amendment Act 2007 was passed, which replaced the use of the Seal of Niue in Tokelau and substituted it with "under the hand of the [[Administrator of Tokelau]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz/gpacts/public/text/2007/se/084se8.html |title=Amendments to Tokelau Islands Crimes Regulations 1975 |publisher=Legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz |date=20 September 2007 |accessdate=16 July 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726143245/http://legislation.knowledge-basket.co.nz/gpacts/public/text/2007/se/084se8.html |archivedate=26 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
==Design== The Seal of Niue has at its centre the [[coat of arms]] of New Zealand, which is a shield divided into quarters. In the first quarter is the [[constellation]] of the [[Southern Cross]], in the second a golden fleece, a sheaf of wheat in the third, and two crossed hammers in the fourth. Over the four-quarters in the centre appears a white band on which there are three black ships. The shield is supported by a woman dressed in a white robe carrying the flag of New Zealand, representing the population that descended from European immigrants (mainly British), and a Maori warrior armed with a spear, representing the indigenous population. At the head of the shield is a crown, and at the foot of the shield is a ribbon with the words "New Zealand". The Seal is on a white circle, with "Public Seal of Niue" along the top, and "Niue" at the bottom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hubert-herald.nl/NewZealandTerritories.htm |title=New Zealand Territories |publisher=Hubert Herald |date= |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref>
