{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}} {{Italic title}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = File:Joseph Mallord William Turner - Snow Storm - Steam-Boat off a Harbour's Mouth - WGA23178.jpg | painting_alignment = Front | image_size = 454px | title = Snow Storm | alt = Steam-Boat off a Harbour's Mouth | artist = [[J. M. W. Turner]] | year = 1842 | medium = oil on canvas | height_metric =91 | width_metric =122 | length_metric = | height_imperial =36 | width_imperial =48 | length_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = London, Great Britain | museum = [[Tate]] | owner = }}
'''''Snow Storm''''', or '''''Snow Storm: Steam-Boat off a Harbour's Mouth''''', (full title: '''''Snow Storm – Steam-Boat off a Harbour's Mouth Making Signals in Shallow Water, and going by the Lead. The Author was in this Storm on the Night the "Ariel" left Harwich''''')<ref name=Rodner/> is a painting by English artist [[Joseph Mallord William Turner]] (1775–1851) from 1842.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/turner-snow-storm-steam-boat-off-a-harbours-mouth-n00530|title=Snow Storm – Steam-Boat off a Harbour's Mouth|publisher=www.tate.org.uk|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-britain/display/turner-collection|title=Turner-collection|publisher=www.tate.org.uk|accessdate=}}</ref>
Though panned by many contemporary critics, critic [[John Ruskin]] commented in 1843 that it was "one of the very grandest statements of sea-motion, mist and light, that has ever been put on canvas".
==History==
An inscription on the painting relates that ''The Author was in this Storm on the Night the "Ariel" left Harwich''. Turner later recounted a story about the background of the painting: {{cquote|I did not paint it to be understood, but I wished to show what such a scene was like; I got the sailors to lash me to the mast to observe it; I was lashed for four hours, and I did not expect to escape, but I felt bound to record it if I did.{{sfnp|Bockemühl|2015|p=71}}}}
He was 67 years old at the time.<ref name=hall>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=James|title=A sublime roller coaster ride through art history|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/context-comment/articles/sublime-roller-coaster-ride-through-art-history|website=tate.org.uk|publisher=Tate Britain|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>{{sfnp|Beckett|1994|p=243}} Some later commentators doubt the literal truth of this account.<ref name=Rodner/> Other critics accept Turner's account, and one wrote, "He empathized completely with the dynamic form of sovereign nature."<ref>Bockemühl, Michael and Mallor, Joseph, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=pnIowKHirrkC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA69&focus=viewport&dq= Turner]'', pages 69–73, [[Taschen]], 2000,</ref> This inscription allows us to better understand the scene represented and the confusion of elements.
Turner had investigated the interactions between nature and the new technology of steamboats in at least five paintings in the previous decade.<ref name=Rodner/> Throughout his career, Turner engaged with issues of urbanism, industry, railroads and steam power.<ref name=Rodner/> The paddle steamer ''"Ariel"'' was formerly called the ''"Arrow"'', being built in 1821–1822. In 1837 she was acquired by the Admiralty and renamed ''"Ariel"'', and was used as the Dover packet up to 1846.<ref name=ariel>{{cite web|title=The Paddle Steamer 'Ariel' by Samuel Walters|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/the-paddle-steamer-ariel-175975|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>
Early critical response to the painting was largely negative, with one critic calling it "soapsuds and whitewash".<ref name=Rodner>Rodner, William, [https://books.google.com/books?id=wgS2nYRIuUEC&pg=PA1063&dq=turner+ Encyclopedia of the Romantic Era, 1760–1850 – M-Z], [[Taylor and Francis]], 2004</ref> [[John Ruskin]], the leading English art critic of the Victorian era, though, wrote in 1843 in his book ''[[Modern Painters]]'' that the painting was "one of the very grandest statements of sea-motion, mist and light, that has ever been put on canvas."<ref name=Rodner/> Reportedly Turner was hurt by the criticism, repeating "soapsuds and whitewash" over and over again, and saying, "What would they have? I wonder what they think the sea's like? I wish they'd been in it". Ruskin commented, "It is thus, too often, that ignorance sits in judgment on the works of genius".<ref>{{cite book|last=Thornbury|first=Walter|authorlink=George Walter Thornbury|title=The Life of J.M.W. Turner, R.A.: Founded on Letters and Papers Furnished by His Friends and Fellow-academicians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iwrWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA407|year=1904|publisher=Chatto & Windus|pages=407–408}}</ref> More recently, art historian Alexandra Wettlaufer wrote that the painting is one of Turner's "most famous, and most obscure, sublime depictions".<ref>{{cite book|last=Wettlaufer|first=Alexandra|title=In the Mind's Eye: The Visual Impulse in Diderot, Baudelaire and Ruskin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xI5ymCe5j0oC&pg=PA278|year=2003|publisher=Rodopi|isbn=9789042010352|pages=278–79}}</ref>
Currently in the collection of the [[Tate]] in London, it was on exhibition at the [[De Young Museum]] in San Francisco in 2015.<ref name=deyoung>{{cite web|title=J. M. W. Turner: Painting Set Free|url=http://deyoung.famsf.org/exhibitions/j-m-w-turner-painting-set-free|website=deyoung.famsf.org|publisher=Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>
==Painting== [[File:J.M.W. Turner, R.A. (1775-1851), Storm at Sea.Christie's.jpg|thumb|Turner's watercolour, ''Storm at Sea'']] The painting depicts a [[paddle steamer]] caught in a snow storm. This [[marine painting]] is showing a Romantic era's painter's depiction of a snowstorm on water at its best, fully developing the bold, daring Romantic fantasy of Turner. Turner was unrivaled in depicting the natural world unmastered by mankind and exploring the effects of the elements and the battle of the forces of the nature. Turner worked first as a [[watercolorist]], and he started to work much later with oils. He later applied the techniques he learned in watercolour onto oil paintings.{{sfnp|Beckett|1994|ps=page 194, 263–268}}
It is typical of the late style of Turner. Turner's tints and shades of colours are painted in different layers of colour, the brushstrokes adding texture to the painting. The colours are monochromatic, only a few shades of grey, green and brown are present, having the same tone of colours. The silvery pale light that surrounds the boat creates a focal point, drawing the viewer into the painting. The smoke from the steamboat spreads out over the sky, creating abstract shapes of the same quality like the waves.<ref>The Art Book, 1994 Phaidon Press Limited, {{ISBN|9780714829845}} page 465-467 -</ref><!--<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Book-Editors-Phaidon-Press/dp/B00CC6E7V8|title=Phaidon-Press, The Art Book |publisher=www.amazon.com|accessdate=}}</ref> --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/567616.The_Art_Book |title=goodreads The Art Book |publisher=www.goodreads.com|accessdate=}}</ref> <!--<ref>{{cite web|url=|title=|publisher=| page 194, 263–268}}</ref> marine painting, bold, aqvarell, like a modern painting-->
