The '''Sydney University Dramatic Society''' ('''SUDS''') is the premier body for the production of undergraduate theatre at the [[University of Sydney]]. Established formally in 1889, with performances dating back to 1883, the society is the oldest continual theatre company in Australia, and one of the oldest student theatre groups in the world.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Dear Descendants|author=Gunn, J.|publisher=john gunn|isbn=9780977580149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZ3w67iiIF8C|page=66|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref><ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-05-21/sydney-university-dramatic-society-celebrates-125th-anniversary/6485036</ref> Supported by the [[University of Sydney Union]], SUDS performs over 16 productions a year,<ref name="sydney">{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/current_students/life/cultural_life.shtml|title=Cultural life - Current students - The University of Sydney|publisher=sydney.edu.au|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref> all of which are directed, designed and performed by its members. As well as traditional theatre, SUDS has been involved in the production and staging of student written productions, experimental plays, improvised theatre, and various [[University of Sydney Revues|comedy revues]].<ref name="google2">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gXVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yeQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7224%2C4493738|title=The Sydney Morning Herald - Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref>
SUDS currently operates out of the society's own production space, the Cellar Theatre, underneath the Holme Building on the Camperdown Campus of the [[University of Sydney]]. Before this plays were regularly housed in [[St James' Hall, Sydney|St James' Hall]] and the Society's own performance space on George Street,<ref name="google"/> with smaller productions housed in the University's Footbridge and Wallace Theatres.
During the society's heyday SUDS was considered one of the leading production companies in Australia, attracting a range of theatrical talent and audiences beyond its student base.<ref name="nla">{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article51398407|title=16 Mar 1960 - Big hand for 'Open House'|publisher=trove.nla.gov.au|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref> This popularity peaked in the postwar years of the 1950s-60s during which time a large number of prominent actors and personalities passed through its ranks. SUDS is considered to have played a leading role in the establishment of Australian theatre, alongside breakaway group The Sydney Players, during this time.<ref name="google"/><ref name="usyd">{{cite web|url=http://ojs-prod.library.usyd.edu.au/index.php/HUL/article/view/5346|title=The Ripples Before the (New) Wave: SUDS, Players and the College Dramatic Societies at the University of Sydney, 1957-61 &#124; Ginters &#124; History of University Life|publisher=ojs-prod.library.usyd.edu.au|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref><ref name="imodules">{{cite web|url=https://secureau.imodules.com/s/965/images/editor_documents/alumni-magazine/10-march/SAM_cover-story_Mar10.pdf|date=20 April 2010|title=All the world's a stage|author=Elissa Blake|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref>
==Alumni== {{refimprove section|date=November 2016}} SUDS has nurtured a number of notable alumni who have gone on to excel in the arts, most notably [[John Bell (Australian actor)|John Bell]] [[Order of Australia|AO]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], who went on to found the [[Bell Shakespeare Company]] following his time at the University of Sydney.<ref name="imodules"/> Other notable members have included Gough Whitlam, a future Prime Minister of Australia, who met his wife Margaret through SUDS,<ref name="google3">{{cite book|title=Gough Whitlam|author=Hocking, J.|date=2008|volume=1|publisher=Miegunyah Press|isbn=9780522855111|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6PR3CEn4168C|page=76|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref> and personalities Germaine Greer and Clive James both of whom went on to manage the [[Cambridge Footlights]] during its golden era.
Past members and people associated with SUDS productions include: {{div col|colwidth=22em}} *[[Neil Armfield]] *[[John Bell (Australian actor)|John Bell]] *[[Arthur Dignam]] *[[Nick Enright]] *[[Charles Firth (comedian)|Charles Firth]] *[[John Gaden]] *[[Virginia Gay]] *[[Germaine Greer]] *[[Andrew Hansen]] *[[Robert Jarman]] *[[Dominic Knight]] *[[Chas Licciardello]] *[[David Marr (journalist)|David Marr]] *[[Julian Morrow]] *[[Tommy Murphy (Australian playwright)|Tommy Murphy]] *[[Andrew O'Keefe]] *[[Marion Potts]] *[[Craig Reucassel]] *[[Leo Schofield|Anne and Leo Schofield]]<ref>
